  "why": "CrossASR++ enforces semantic consistency by design and validates whether synthesized inputs actually preserve the original text semantics before treating a mismatch as a failure: it synthesizes audio from an unchanged input text (no iterative semantic mutations), cross-references multiple ASRs, and only marks an input as a failed test when the System Under Test (SUT) disagrees with the original text while at least one other ASR agrees — cases where no ASR recognizes the text are treated as 'indeterminable' (i.e., potentially invalid TTS outputs) rather than as failures. Naturalness is preserved because the tool uses realistic TTS engines (e.g., Google TTS, ResponsiveVoice, Festival, Espeak) to generate audio rather than applying arbitrary or accumulating distortions; the design avoids iterative mutations that could accumulate semantic drift. Together, these elements satisfy the High level: semantic consistency is enforced/validated where the oracle assumes equivalence, and inputs are realistic (TTS-generated) across the testing process.",
